Let's consider the tanh RNN equation (see above). When computing the gradient of the global error E with respect to the parameter U, in the case where we have 3 inputs, how many gradients will we end up summing? 

(x) 6 {{U has been used in 1 place only when computing the gradient of E0 with respect to U, in 2 places when computing the gradient of E1 with respect to U, and in 3 places when computing the gradient of E2 with respect to U.}}
( ) 3 {{Remember that U can be used multiple times in the computation graph when computing the gradient of a single error Et.}}
( ) 1 {{Remember that the global error E is composed of all the errors Et at every step.}}
( ) 9 {{Remember that only the current and past elements contribute to the output that affects a given error.}}
